ce:section.ce:para:
The pH of the precursor solution influences the degree of polymerization, crosslinking, and carbonization in the reaction process, and ultimately make a difference in the structure and PL property of CDs. Under the acidic environment, the two amino groups of 2,3-diaminopyridine are protonated, and therefore possess high electrophilicity. The protonated NH3
                        + group of the precursor in the acidic condition is more reactive than the non-protonated NH2 group in the neutral or alkaline condition, and can attack the electron-rich pyridine ring of another precursor molecule more easily. Thus, the lower pH condition leads to a deeper polymerization by addition of 2,3-diaminopyridine monomer. Fig. S4 depicts some possible reactions happened in the formation process of CDs [42–44]. After further crosslinking and carbonization at high temperature of 180 °C, the lower pH condition results in the production of CDs with a larger size of sp2 domain and a higher level of graphitic nitrogen, which own a narrower band gap and emit a longer wavelength PL (Fig. 4
                        ).
